241825	AM I THE DRAMA?	Cardi B	44.16	https://static.qobuz.com/images/covers/va/6u/k2kc4lmlx6uva_600.jpg	qobuz:343004769|k2kc4lmlx6uva	Does it feel like Cardi B ever went away? That is, if you merely consumed rap via Hot 97, would you notice she hadn't released an album in seven years? While fans have certainly awaited the follow-up to her 2018 instant classic debut Invasion of Privacy with frothy fervor on social media, it hadn't become a running joke like waiting for Guns N' Roses' Chinese Democracy or a still-yet-to-materialize follow-up to Rihanna's great Anti. Because not only did Belcalis Almánzar never disappear from the cultural landscape, but she also continued to define the genre in the 2020s with standalone songs that were enormous events in themselves ("WAP" and "Up," both included here; the underrated "Bongos") and some of the best cameos of the last decade (Latto's "Put It on Da Floor Again," GloRilla's "Tomorrow 2"). Even Privacy outtake "Money" smoked almost anything else from the era. So her long-brewing sophomore effort feels less like a major cultural comeback than a summary compendium from an essential icon.It remains a thrill whenever Cardi opens her mouth, as on the first single "Imaginary Playerz," where she nerdily boasts, "I seen whole fan pages make avatar changes," or the hyperactive "Bodega Baddie," where she compares herself to Selena. Her emotional content deserves more attention, not least because the bite of her voice sells the heartbreak in lines like "now I've got a ring on every finger but the one on my ring hand" and "you was me but the evil version" from the Offset-lamenting "Be Careful" denouement "Man of Your Word." But Cardi remains at her best over a ferocious cut like "Outside," ("Let me know the time and place/ I'm just tryna ride his face") which grafts a Pop Smoke bassline onto classic NOLA bounce. The palette is significantly more R&B than her debut, with luminaries as disparate as Tyla, Summer Walker, and a sampled Janet Jackson (on the lovely "Principal," which warns "take me anywhere but don't take me for granted") on hand to occasionally coo over softcore like "On My Back" ("I want to hold it when you pee"); even the rare appearance by a young rapper is "sexy drill" purveyor Cash Cobain, who's accustomed to rapping between the sheets. At almost 80 minutes, anyone could whittle AM I THE DRAMA? down to their ideal follow-up (start by chopping Lizzo singing 4 Non Blondes on "What's Goin On"), but don't dare peace out before that seismic "Up" and "WAP" encore. It's Cardi's drama, we just live in it. © Daniel Aaron/Qobuz	39	CD	2026-01-18 21:52:11.829124	2
