539013	I Said I Love You First	Selena Gomez	173.55	https://static.qobuz.com/images/covers/na/o4/bau5v1w10o4na_600.jpg	qobuz:325739226|bau5v1w10o4na	It can be a risky proposition to take your love story public, let alone make it the centerpiece of your art (hello, J. Lo). But Selena Gomez and her producer fiancé Benny Blanco are all in on the singer's fourth album. Despite having only dated for a couple of years, they've been musical accomplices for a decade, and I Said I Love You First charts their relationship from friendship to engagement. Gomez—who has a good history with horn-dog songs ("Bad Liar," "Hands to Myself")—is mostly in a playful mood, particularly on "Sunset Blvd," which seems to draw inspiration from Japanese city pop and is laden with innuendo: "I just wanna touch it, touch it/ Try your hardest not to bust it/ Give me, give me, how I love your big, big … heart." That's immediately followed by "Cowboy," a slow-drift jam that takes things to the next base ("Put your hands on me/ Ride it like a cowboy") and pulls in GloRilla for an explicit outro verse that sounds like a voicenote. Gomez is also not above cutting a new lover's too-friendly friend out of the picture with the buttery, fluttery "Don't Take It Personally." And she reaches into her past to re-examine an old betrayal ("Don't Wanna Cry," a gently turning mirror ball with a sultry beat) and shake off a vivid dream about an ex in "You Said You Were Sorry," which finds her sounding ethereal and even Lana del Rey-esque. In an unusual move, Gomez and Blanco include a collaborative single from 2019, the reggaeton-flavored "I Can't Get Enough" with guest J Balvin and a memorable "mm-mm-mm-mm" hook. It's interesting to hear the six-year-old song again here, as a sort of living testimony to how Gomez's vocal style has been evolving. Long gone is the slightly scratchy style of 2014's giddy fun "Love You Like a Love Song," in favor of the softness she's been moving toward for a while. While her voice ca