hink she's pretty," she sings, offering a look into the trappings of fame in the modern age. "When I step off the stage, I'm a bird in a cage … And the internet is hungry for the meanest kinda funny/ And somebody's gotta feed it." But there's plenty of fun here, too. Bass-heavy "Lunch," which acknowledges the singer being newly out about her sexuality, feels like a cousin to her breakthrough "Bad Guy"; the song coyly slithers, but wolfish Eilish is straightforward, panting "I could eat that girl for lunch" over goth synth. "Birds of a Feather" is a giddy nod to mid-'80s radio pop. "CHIHIRO"—named for the hero of the Hayao Miyazaki movie Spirited Away—has an elastic, trance-like '90s vibe. And slinky "THE DINER" dips into French-kissed Romany pop. It all ends with "BLUE," which travels from moody pop to stark ballad to cool, robo-effect hip-hop and drops lyrical Easter eggs that seem to reference the album's other songs before Eilish acknowledges the world's insatiability: "Now when can I hear the next one?" © Shelly Ridenour/Qobuz	14	CD	2026-01-18 21:54:04.899805	2
