938691	GNX	Kendrick Lamar	396	https://static.qobuz.com/images/covers/3b/rj/n9dqr0t48rj3b_600.jpg	qobuz:302791418|n9dqr0t48rj3b	Of all the facets of his artistry, Kendrick Lamar possesses two crucial strengths that, in tandem, spark a compelling struggle. One is his formidable ability, per hip-hop's tradition, of savvily synthesizing multiple generations' worth of musical and cultural influence to speak to the present through the past. The other is a tendency to interrogate himself over the ensuing internal contradictions that result from this. As an MC from a generation that was catalyzed by 2Pac, Nas, and OutKast, and then set about embodying those artists' own personal turmoil through creative restlessness, Kendrick's ability to thrive on conflict includes the ones that arise within himself. GNX was dropped out of nowhere in the waning weeks of a 2024 that was already under his command—the realm of a man who, at least for the time being, had summoned an incandescent haterism to dethrone one of pop music's most dominant forces of the last fifteen years. But this album isn't a simple turbocharged victory lap in a Reagan-era muscle car.After sharpening his steel against Drake, Lamar's blade turns inwards, even as he glowers at the peers who frustrate him while he wields it. He kicks off in the mode of an embattled artist who feels under-respected in "wacced out murals" and uses that bitterness to fuel the individualistic chest-pounding of "squabble up"'s freestyle-goes-Zapp elasticity, front-loading the album with a brittle-edged and deceptively indulgent ego trip that culminates in the entitlement-justifying I deserve it all grasp of "man at the garden." It's in the conceptual insight of "reincarnated" that he questions all this—his role as an artist struggling with the pull between his ego, the power the music business has given him, and the effect his work has on its listeners. From there it's a different kind of confidence. "tv off" rattles with a demand for tougher competition as though he's warding off his own complacency, "dodger blue" and the title cut lift up the city and the potential rap heirs that he maintains strong ties to, and "heart pt. 6" serves as a reflective reminder of the come-up that put him on the road to where he is today. As pure music, GNX is resonant in both its familiarity and its boldness: Sounwave's expansive palette infuses the album's retrofuture g-funk with slow jams ("luther"), hyphy ("peekaboo"), chillwave ("dodger blue"), and the in-the-air-tonight minimalism of Nas's "One Mic" ("man at the garden"); between that and Mustard's instantly-legendary "Not Like Us"-redux "tv off" it's even possible to forget Jack Antonoff's hand in it. And there's a real dynamism when it's paired with the stylistic malleability of Lamar's own flows—whether it's the self-interrogation of "reincarnated," the Drakeo the Ruler stylistic tribute on "hey now," or the melodic lilt of SZA-featuring state-of-his-art closer "gloria." GNX is the sound of a man looking for a resolution, something to tie all the loose ends together and show him and his art form a possible new escape route out from an encroaching disillusionment. © Nate Patrin/Qobuz	13	Vinyl	2026-01-18 21:56:20.99281	1
843955	DAMN.	Kendrick Lamar	91.2	https://static.qobuz.com/images/covers/71/08/0060255760871_600.jpg	qobuz:40128300|0060255760871	To Pimp a Butterfly's proper and oft-biblical follow-up arrived on Good Friday, 13 months after untitled unmastered., an intermediary release that eclipsed the best work of most contemporary artists. If Kendrick Lamar felt pressure to continue living up to his previous output, there's no evidence on DAMN. He's too occupied tracing the spectrum of his mental states, from "boxin' demons" to "flex on swole," questioning and reveling in his affluence, castigating and celebrating his bloodline, humble enough to relate his vulnerabilities, assured enough to proclaim "Ain't none of y'all fuckin' with the flow." Throughout, he intensely examines most of the seven deadly sins, aware all along that his existence is threatened by anyone who objects to the color of his skin or clothes -- or, in the case of the blind stranger who shoots him during the album's opener, nothing that is apparent. Compared to the maximum-capacity, genre-twisting vastness and winding narratives of Good Kid, M.A.A.D. City and To Pimp a Butterfly, DAMN. on the surface seems like a comparatively simple rap album that demands less from the listener. There's relative concision in the track titles and material, and a greater emphasis on commercial sounds -- such as Mike WiLL's lean and piano-laced trap beat for the strong-arming "HUMBLE.," Lamar's first Top Ten pop hit, and a couple productions that are merely functional backdrops lacking distinction. In a way, however, DAMN. is just as lavish and singular as the preceding albums, its quantity and weight of thoughts and connected concepts condensed into a considerably tighter space. It contains some of Lamar's best writing and performances, revealing his evolving complexity and versatility as a soul-baring lyricist and dynamic rapper. Although it's occasionally distorted, stretched, smeared, and reversed to compelling and imagination-fueling effect, his voice is at its most affecting in its many untreated forms. Take "FEAR.," in which he switches between echoing hot-blooded parental threats to enumerating, with a 40-acre stare, various death scenarios. His storytelling hits an astonishing new high on "Duckworth," the album's finale. Over ethereal funk sewn by 9th Wonder, Lamar details a potentially tragic encounter between his father and future Top Dawg CEO Anthony Tiffith -- and the conditions leading to it -- that occurred long before Kung Fu Kenny was known as K. Dot.© Andy Kellman /TiVo	14	CD	2026-01-18 21:56:34.711433	2
