153539	Addison	Addison Rae	241.01	https://static.qobuz.com/images/covers/8b/f1/d9jbuk2z2f18b_600.jpg	qobuz:339562548|d9jbuk2z2f18b	Addison Rae, at 24, is the poster girl for modern fame. After going viral at 18 for TikTok videos of her dancing to pop songs, she left college and signed with a mega talent agency, then co-hosted a podcast with her mom. A failed first single led her to debut EP being scrapped, but she launched perfume and cosmetic lines, tried her hand at acting and eventually released a few more songs to better reception. Then, in 2024, Charli XCX and A.G. Cook—the pop star and producer, respectively, of that summer—embraced Rae by featuring her on a remix of "Von dutch" and the song "Lucifer" from Cook's Britpop album. But it was Rae's own single, "Diet Pepsi," that finally hit big, creating a "What is that?!" moment. Suddenly, Addison Rae was taken seriously as more than just a novelty. The release of her debut album has her poised to be the girl of this summer, but the question still remains: Who, exactly, is she? Last year, we had Charli XCX's rule-breaking hedonism and Sabrina Carpenter's knowing pin-up wink and Chappell Roan's campy but poignant drag posture. Along with co-producers Luka Kloser and Elvira Anderfjärd—two relative unknowns (though Anderfjärd came up through the Max Martin system) who are the only producers and co-writers on all but one song on Addison—Rae seems to be still figuring herself out. Heavy-panting dance track "New York" borrows the house beats that propelled Charli's Brat. "Aquamarine" digs deeper into the past, specifically Ray of Light-era Madonna. Fun synth-popper "Fame Is a Gun" could be a retro Britney Spears track right down to the baby-doll vocals; not for nothing, Rae and Spears are both from small-town Louisiana and, as Rae sings here, "It never was enough/ I always wanted more." But the godmother of Addison is Lana del Rey circa 2012, when her Born to Die featured a song called "Diet Mountain Dew." Rae's memorable "Diet Pepsi" cracks the formula Lana perfected early on, mixing up alt-pop and trip-hop and a breathy sadcore sigh that Rae interprets as sex appeal. She coos and feathers her voice on the Lana-ish "Summer Forever" and dreams of "a cigarette pressed between my tits" on minor-chord-heavy "High Fashion." And Rae isn't hiding it. She name-checks Madonna, Lana and Gaga on appealingly weird, body-rolling "Money is Everything," which opens with her saying: "When I was growing up, Mama always told me to save my money/ So I never had to rely on a man to take care of me/ But money's not coming with me to heaven/ And I have a lot of it—so can't a girl just have fun?" She's kidding, right? Addison feels good, even if it's ephemeral as the AC blast you get walking into H&M on a hot day. © Shelly Ridenour/Qobuz	19	Vinyl	2026-01-18 21:57:09.11994	1
